{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782914114,"nonce":"1xhJ7BRvGF+8T6/Naz8dsF3pjo8=","kind":"adr","title":"Encryption at rest for the private tier","content_type":"text/markdown"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782914114,"nonce":"naV3XOTofgEF8qsHkd5EEJkuXVs=","body":"---\nstatus: proposed\ndate: 2026-06-28\ndeciders: kref maintainers\n---\n\n# Encryption at rest for the private tier\n\n## Context and Problem Statement\n\nThe `private` tier stores entries that never leave the machine, and ingest\nquarantines detected **secrets** there. Today private entries are stored\n**unencrypted** in `refs/kref-private/*` (no encryption at rest — see the\noverarching spec §11). The new export/import + local-vault recovery feature\n(`docs/superpowers/specs/2026-06-28-private-recovery-export-import-design.md`)\ncopies private data into bundles and a `$XDG_DATA_HOME` vault, which surfaces the\nquestion: should kref encrypt private data at rest, and if so, how?\n\n## Decision Drivers\n\n- Secrets sitting in plaintext on disk are a real exposure if the disk is\n  imaged, backed up to the cloud, or copied.\n- kref's design preference: **prefer established FOSS tools over rolling our own\n  crypto**; avoid owning key management.\n- Encrypting only the *backup* while the live `.git` refs stay plaintext is\n  inconsistent and gives false comfort — the honest scope is the whole tier.\n- Minimize new runtime dependencies and config surface; keep the recovery\n  feature shippable on its own.\n\n## Considered Options\n\n1. **Defer native encryption; compose with external tools (SOPS/age) via the\n   pipe-friendly `kref export` stdout.** kref stays crypto-free.\n2. **Native SOPS integration** — kref shells out to [`sops`](https://github.com/getsops/sops)\n   (age/PGP/KMS backends) to encrypt/decrypt private at rest and/or on export.\n3. **Native `age` integration** — a lighter file-encryptor than SOPS; simpler\n   key model, good fit for \"encrypt this blob\", but fewer backends (no KMS).\n4. **Roll our own (e.g. NaCl/secretbox).** Rejected on principle — owning crypto\n   and key management is a liability.\n\n## Decision Outcome\n\n**Chosen: Option 1 (defer; compose externally) for now**, because it solves the\nrecovery problem without coupling in a crypto dependency or key-management\nsurface, and because encrypting only backups while `.git` stays plaintext would\nbe misleading. `kref export` writes a bundle to stdout, so encrypted backups\nwork today:\n\n```bash\nkref export --tier private - | sops -e --input-type binary --output-type binary /dev/stdin \u003e private.enc\n# or:  kref export --tier private - | age -r \u003crecipient\u003e \u003e private.age\n```\n\nNative at-rest encryption of the whole private tier remains **proposed** and is\na larger, separate effort (it must cover the live refs, not just exports). When\nrevisited, **SOPS** (Option 2) is the leading candidate for its KMS/age/PGP\nbackend flexibility, with **age** (Option 3) as the lighter alternative; this ADR\nshould be superseded by an *accepted* decision at that point.\n\n### Consequences\n\n- Good: recovery ships now; no new dependency; users choose their own\n  encryption posture and tooling.\n- Good: composition (`export | sops`/`age`) is testable and transparent.\n- Bad: the default `$XDG_DATA_HOME` vault and plain bundles are **unencrypted** —\n  documented explicitly, with the encrypt recipe alongside.\n- Neutral: a future `--encrypt` convenience (shelling to SOPS/age) is additive\n  and pre-framed by this ADR.\n\n## More Information\n\n- Recovery design:\n  `docs/superpowers/specs/2026-06-28-private-recovery-export-import-design.md`\n  (local, git-ignored).\n- SOPS: \u003chttps://github.com/getsops/sops\u003e · age: \u003chttps://github.com/FiloSottile/age\u003e"}]}